00:57:45.530 --> 00:57:46.530
nothing can leave our universe.

00:57:46.530 --> 00:57:48.113
Our universe would
just be everything.

00:57:51.140 --> 00:57:55.990
I'm using the word
universe instead

00:57:55.990 --> 00:57:58.260
to refer to simply everything
which we can possibly

00:57:58.260 --> 00:58:01.300
observe with even the best
telescopes, namely this sphere

00:58:01.300 --> 00:58:03.990
from which light has had time
to reach us during the 13.8

00:58:03.990 --> 00:58:05.660
billion years
since our Big Bang.

00:58:05.660 --> 00:58:07.260
If you want to be
more precise, you'd

00:58:07.260 --> 00:58:09.320
call this our
observable universe.

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:12.120
If you want to have a
word for everything you

00:58:12.120 --> 00:58:14.137
get to if you travel
forever in all directions,

00:58:14.137 --> 00:58:15.720
I would use a different
word for that.

00:58:15.720 --> 00:58:17.280
Mainly, just space.

00:58:17.280 --> 00:58:20.890
So space is bigger
than our universe.

00:58:20.890 --> 00:58:23.220
We don't know for
sure yet whether space

00:58:23.220 --> 00:58:25.239
is infinite or not.

00:58:25.239 --> 00:58:27.030
It might curve back on
itself or something.

00:58:27.030 --> 00:58:28.800
But right now, we
have no evidence

00:58:28.800 --> 00:58:31.300
whatsoever that space ends here.

00:58:31.300 --> 00:58:33.320
In fact, if we wait
one hour, we can

00:58:33.320 --> 00:58:35.160
see light reach us
from farther away

00:58:35.160 --> 00:58:38.570
and falsify that hypothesis.

00:58:38.570 --> 00:58:41.340
And moreover, inflation,
this most popular theory

00:58:41.340 --> 00:58:43.070
we have for what
created our Big Bang,

00:58:43.070 --> 00:58:44.720
typically predict
that space actually

00:58:44.720 --> 00:58:48.720
is much bigger than this,
perhaps even infinite.

00:58:48.720 --> 00:58:54.510
So we're in this situation
where most likely,

00:58:54.510 --> 00:58:57.222
we can only observe a part
of everything that exists.

00:58:57.222 --> 00:58:58.930
And some people don't
like that, and they

00:58:58.930 --> 00:59:04.390
feel it's disappointing
and humbling.

00:59:04.390 --> 00:59:06.390
They think it's bad for
our egos or whatever.

00:59:06.390 --> 00:59:09.010
But frankly, I think a little
bit of humility is good for us

00:59:09.010 --> 00:59:09.510
humans.

00:59:09.510 --> 00:59:13.742
And second, if we think about
it the other way around, to me,

00:59:13.742 --> 00:59:15.200
it feels pretty
arrogant if we were

00:59:15.200 --> 00:59:17.116
to assume that there's
some law of nature that

00:59:17.116 --> 00:59:19.880
says that we have to be able to
observe everything that exists.

00:59:19.880 --> 00:59:22.173
It's like an ostrich with
its head in the sand,

00:59:22.173 --> 00:59:27.320
saying, oh, if I can't see
you, then you don't exist.

00:59:27.320 --> 00:59:29.260
That feels way too
arrogant for me.

00:59:29.260 --> 00:59:31.280
We humans have had this
tendency in history,

00:59:31.280 --> 00:59:34.050
again, and again, and again,
to assume that everything

00:59:34.050 --> 00:59:36.180
we knew of was
everything that existed.

00:59:36.180 --> 00:59:40.700
That's why we got so freaked
out by the whole Galileo spat,

00:59:40.700 --> 00:59:43.550
and then with the
realities that we

00:59:43.550 --> 00:59:46.944
live in a galaxy, the
universe, and so on.

00:59:46.944 --> 00:59:48.360
I think it's
overwhelmingly likely

00:59:48.360 --> 00:59:51.362
that there are parts of
space that we can't see now.

00:59:51.362 --> 00:59:52.820
Many of these
galaxies out here, we

00:59:52.820 --> 00:59:54.570
can see if we wait
the billion years.

00:59:54.570 --> 00:59:55.319
Eat your vitamins.

00:59:57.427 --> 01:00:00.010
But there might be other regions
of space which you will never

01:00:00.010 --> 01:00:03.070
be able to see, because the dark
energy will keep pushing them

01:00:03.070 --> 01:00:04.840
away from us farther.

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:06.680
Let me also just
comment on the thing

01:00:06.680 --> 01:00:08.360
you said about speed of light.

01:00:08.360 --> 01:00:12.120
So we all learned
in kindergarten

01:00:12.120 --> 01:00:14.680
that nothing can go faster
than the speed of light.

01:00:14.680 --> 01:00:16.640
But it turns out
actually that that's only

01:00:16.640 --> 01:00:18.120
what special relativity said.

01:00:18.120 --> 01:00:20.890
And then Einstein came along
with general relativity

01:00:20.890 --> 01:00:22.760
that overruled this.

01:00:22.760 --> 01:00:24.910
And general relativity
is a bit more liberal

01:00:24.910 --> 01:00:26.360
about the speed limit.

01:00:26.360 --> 01:00:29.340
In general relativity, you
can't go faster than light

01:00:29.340 --> 01:00:32.465
through space itself,
but space can stretch out

01:00:32.465 --> 01:00:34.174
as fast as it wants.

01:00:34.174 --> 01:00:36.340
General relativity says
that space is better thought

01:00:36.340 --> 01:00:38.240
of not as a static
boring stage where

01:00:38.240 --> 01:00:40.590
stuff happens, but
as a rubber sheet.

01:00:40.590 --> 01:00:41.450
It can vibrate.

01:00:41.450 --> 01:00:43.570
That's what those
gravitational waves are.

01:00:43.570 --> 01:00:46.260
It can curve, even making
things like black holes.

01:00:46.260 --> 01:00:47.660
And it can stretch.

01:00:47.660 --> 01:00:49.260
That's what the
expanding universe is.

01:00:49.260 --> 01:00:51.860
So if you keep
stretching it uniformly,

01:00:51.860 --> 01:00:55.050
there will be some parts of
space which right now actually

01:00:55.050 --> 01:00:58.180
are going away from us faster
than the speed of light.

01:00:58.180 --> 01:00:59.430
And that's OK.

01:00:59.430 --> 01:01:01.680
If you try to look at them,
you simply can't see them.

01:01:01.680 --> 01:01:04.780
Light hasn't made it over here.

01:01:04.780 --> 01:01:06.840
So on that note, I
think time is up.

01:01:06.840 --> 01:01:08.710
So let me thank you
all so much for coming.

01:01:08.710 --> 01:01:09.840
It was a pleasure.

01:01:09.840 --> 01:01:13.490
[APPLAUSE]

